description: From Middle French parall√®le, borrowed from Latin parallelus.

entries.meaning: Equally distant from one another at all points.
examples: The horizontal lines on my notebook paper are parallel.

entries.meaning: Having the same overall direction; the comparison is indicated with "to".
examples: The two railway lines are parallel.

entries.meaning: (hyperbolic geometry, said of a pair of lines) Either not intersecting, or coinciding.
(computing) Involving the processing of multiple tasks at the same time.

adverbs.description: parallel (comparative more parallel, superlative most parallel)

entries.meaning: With a parallel relationship.
examples: The road runs parallel to the canal.

entries.meaning: One of a set of parallel lines.
Direction conformable to that of another line.
examples: lines that from their parallel decline

entries.meaning: A line of latitude.
examples: The 31st parallel passes through the center of my town.

entries.meaning: An arrangement of electrical components such that a current flows along two or more paths; see in parallel.
Something identical or similar in essential respects.
A comparison made; elaborate tracing of similarity.
examples: Johnson's parallel between Dryden and Pope

entries.meaning: (military) One of a series of long trenches constructed before a besieged fortress, by the besieging force, as a cover for troops supporting the attacking batteries. They are roughly parallel to the line of outer defenses of the fortress.
(printing) A character consisting of two parallel vertical lines, used in the text to direct attention to a similarly marked note in the margin or at the foot of a page.

verbs.description: parallel (third-person singular simple present parallels, present participle (US) paralleling or (UK) parallelling, simple past and past participle (US) paralleled or (UK) parallelled)

entries.meaning: To construct or place something parallel to something else.
Of a path etc: To be parallel to something else.
examples: Archaic covered bridges lingered fearsomely out of the past in pockets of the hills, and the half-abandoned railway track paralleling the river seemed to exhale a nebulously visible air of desolation.

entries.meaning: Of a process etc: To be analogous to something else.
To compare or liken something to something else.
To make to conform to something else in character, motive, aim, etc.
To equal; to match; to correspond to.
To produce or adduce as a parallel.
examples: Who cannot parallel these stories out of his experience?
